"# Appendix 10 — \"The next Python\" checklist

<!-- covers-through: 2026-07-11 -->

Seven criteria that made Python \"the next Python\" — and Motoi Scheme's status on each.

---

## The seven criteria

| # | Criterion | Python's answer | Motoi Scheme's answer | Status |
|---:|---|---|---|:---:|
| 1 | **Batteries included** | `re`, `os`, `datetime`, `json`, `http`, `sqlite3` | 68 namespaces × 1,157 verbs | ✅ shipping |
| 2 | **One canonical way** | `python -m` + PEP 8 | `sakura-scheme fmt` (Jess 12.4 #17) + REFERENCE canon | ✅ shipping / v1.0 |
| 3 | **Great REPL** | `>>>` + IPython | 21-trick REPL (Appendix 3) + `,ask sakura` | ✅ shipping |
| 4 | **Readable syntax for newcomers** | indent-sensitive, English-like | S-expressions + rainbow parens + LSP + `describe` | 🟡 subjective |
| 5 | **Works everywhere** | CPython + PyPy + micropython | CLI + WASM + npm embed + browser | ✅ shipping |
| 6 | **Docs that don't lie** | official docs + docstrings | THE-BOOK autogen from `env.define` + doctest (Jess 12.2 #10) | 🟡 building |
| 7 | **A community with taste** | PSF + PEP process | Lacuna Engineering + adversarial protocol + Alfred | 🟢 forming |

## Where we're better

- **AI as a peer in the REPL** — `,ask sakura` is not a chatbot bolt-on; the persona reads your session bindings and returns runnable code. No language has this shipping.
- **Slat serialization for free** — every record + hash + session persists to disk with `(slat/save x)`. Structured serialization by construction, no untrusted-blob-deserialization landmines.
- **Rich error records** — Python's tracebacks are strings; Sakura's are structured slat that `sakura/fix` reads.
- **First-class artifacts** — the grand-unifier UI surface. No language has \"put the game and the shop and the chat on the same surface\" as a first-class primitive.
- **Contract enforcement at dispatcher** — Python has `typing` at import time; Sakura enforces at every call.

## Where we're weaker (honest)

- **Number of libraries** — Python has 500,000+ PyPI packages. Sakura has 1,157 verbs. Bridge: JS interop via the runtime — `(system/require \"npm-package\")` lands verbs into a namespace. Coverage grows fast when NPM ~= our stdlib.
- **Familiarity** — S-expressions ARE weirder for most devs. Bridge: Appendix 5 answers. But some people just won't come.
- **Editor plugins depth** — Python has a decade of Vim/Emacs/VS Code polish. Sakura's LSP ships day-1 but the editor plugins are v1.
- **Package manager** — no `pip` equivalent yet. Cart signing (Priya 14.3) is the substrate; the CLI ships next.

## The bar we're clearing

The 2020s language to beat isn't Python. It's the AI-coding-agent-first language nobody's shipped yet. Sakura is that language. Every criterion above is \"does an AI + a human pair-programming on this in 2026 feel amplified?\" — and every appendix in this book is an answer.

## Related

- Appendix 2 — the top-10 wow features
- Appendix 3 — the REPL
- Appendix 4 — the autogen verbs (`sakura/complete`, `sakura/rewrite`, `sakura/fix`)
- Appendix 12 — Jess's tooling additions (LSP, doctest, formatter, lint)
")
